		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2017"></a><br><code>sle2017/paper14</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>A formalisation of parameterised reference attribute grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ScottBuckley.html">Scott Buckley</a>, <a href="../profile/AnthonyMSloane.html">Anthony M. Sloane</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136024">10.1145/3136014.3136024</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The paper formalizes parameterised reference attribute grammars as a meta-language formalism.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Its main contribution is a formalisation enabling equivalence/correctness-style reasoning about attribute-grammar systems.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Reference attribute grammars are widely used to define static semantic analyses in language implementations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> Parameterisation is aimed at modular reuse/composition of attribute-grammar components across language fragments.
</li></ul></li></ul>
